CREATE TABLE students (
    id NUMBER PRIMARY KEY, 
    age NUMBER, 
    hobby VARCHAR(50),
    name VARCHAR(50)
);

Step 3: Storing Information (INSERT)
To put data into your newly created table, you use the INSERT INTO command. You specify the table, the columns you want to fill, and the values.

INSERT INTO students (id, age, hobby, name) 
VALUES (1, 18, 'Coding', 'Trishul');

INSERT INTO students (id, age, hobby, name) 
VALUES (2, 19, 'Robotics', 'Rahul');


when you insert data, it is temporarily saved in your current session, but it is not permanently written to the database yet.
To make your changes permanent, you must explicitly tell Oracle to save them:

COMMIT;

To view the data you just stored, you use the SELECT statement. The asterisk (*) acts as a wildcard meaning "all columns."

SELECT * FROM students;
If you only want to see specific columns, you can type their names:

SELECT name, hobby FROM students;
